AXL - Market Data & News
AXL - Stock Valuation Report
 Trade 
American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. (AXL) had a rough trading day for Friday July 21 as 
shares 
tumbled 6.17%, or a loss of $-1.02 per share, to close at $15.50. After opening the day at $16.44, shares of American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. traded as high as $16.46 and as 
low as $15.17. Volume was 2.8 million shares over 15,263 trades, against an average daily volume of 1.57 million shares and a total float of 111.18 million.

As a result of the decline, American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. now has a market cap of $1.72 billion. The stock has a P/E Ratio of 5.1. In the last 
year, shares of American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. have traded between a range of $21.25 and $12.61, and its 50-day SMA is currently $15.80 and 200-day SMA is $17.62. 


For a complete fundamental analysis of American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc., check out Equities.com’s Stock Valuation Analysis report for 
AXL.

Want to invest with the experts? Subscribe to Equities Premium newsletters today! Visit http://www.equitiespremium.com/ to 
learn more about Guild Investment’s Market Commentary  and Adam Sarhan’s 
Find Leading Stocks  today. 

American Axle & Mfg Holdings Inc manufactures, engineers, designs and validates driveline systems and drivetrain components and chassis modules. Its products are mostly used in light trucks, Sports Utility Vehicles, commercial vehicles and passenger cars.

American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. is based out of Detroit, MI and has some 13,100 employees. Its CEO is David C. Dauch.

American Axle & Manufacturing Holdings Inc. is a component of the Russell 2000. The Russell 2000 is one of the leading indices tracking small-cap companies in the United States. It's maintained by  Russell Investments, an 
industry leader in creating and maintaining indices, and consists of the smallest 2000 stocks from the broader Russell 3000 index.


    Russell's indices differ from traditional indices like the Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) or S&P 500, whose members are selected by committee, because they base membership entirely on an 
objective, rules based methodology. The 3,000 largest companies by market cap make up the Russell 3000, with the 2,000 smaller companies making up the Russell 2000. It's a simple approach that gives 
a broad, unbiased look at the small-cap market as a whole.


